  "prompt": "How can I grow a sandalwood tree in my backyard?",
  "response": "Growing a sandalwood tree in your backyard can be challenging, but here are some key steps:\n\n1. Climate requirements\n- Sandalwood trees thrive in tropical and subtropical regions\n- Need warm temperatures between 64-100\u00b0F\n- Prefer areas with annual rainfall of 20-40 inches\n- Best suited for USDA zones 10-11\n\n2. Soil conditions\n- Well-draining, slightly acidic soil (pH 6.0-7.5)\n- Sandy or loamy soil\n- Moderate organic content\n\n3. Planting\n- Requires host plants like neem or acacia for growth\n- Plant seedlings or young trees\n- Space trees about 20-25 feet apart\n- Partial shade is ideal initially\n\n4. Care\n- Regular watering, especially during early growth stages\n- Protect from extreme heat and cold\n- Prune to maintain shape\n- Minimal fertilization needed\n\n5. Considerations\n- Slow-growing tree (takes 15-20 years to mature)\n- Expensive and difficult to cultivate\n- May require special permits in some regions\n- Consider consulting local agricultural experts\n\n6. Alternative\n- If conditions aren't ideal, consider growing in a large pot or greenhouse\n\nNote: Success depends heavily on specific local conditions and careful management.",
